\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Homological Algebra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Chain Complexes over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring.
 A 
\series bold
chain complex
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A:=(A_{\bullet},d_{\bullet})$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
over
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, or simply a 
\series bold
chain complex 
\series default
if the context is clear, is a sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 and morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}:A_{i}\to A_{i-1}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{diagramA}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} (A,d) := 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
arrow[r] & A_{i+1} 
\backslash
arrow[r,"d _{i+1}"] & A_i  
\backslash
arrow[r," d _i "] & A_{i-1} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}\circ d_{i+1}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 The condition 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}\circ d_{i+1}=0$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(d_{i})\supset\text{Im}(d_{i+1})$
\end_inset

.
 With this in mind, we define the 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th
\series default
 
\series bold
homology of the chain complex
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{i}(A):=\text{Ker}(d_{i})/\text{Im}(d_{i+1}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A 
\series bold
chain map
\series default
 between two complexes 
\begin_inset Formula $A=(A_{\bullet},d_{\bullet})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A'=(A'_{\bullet},d'_{\bullet})$
\end_inset

 is a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{\bullet}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}:A_{i}\to A'_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}\varphi_{i-1}=\varphi_{i}d_{i-1}'$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from the definition that a chain map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to A'$
\end_inset

 induces map of homologies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}:H_{i}(A)\to H_{i}(A')$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To simplify notation in what follows, we think of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 as a trivially graded ring.
 If 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{equation}
\backslash
label{diagramA}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} A := 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
arrow[r] & A_{i+1} 
\backslash
arrow[r,"d _{i+1}"] & A_i  
\backslash
arrow[r," d _i "] & A_{i-1} 
\backslash
arrow[r] & 
\backslash
cdots 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a chain complex over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, then we can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as a graded 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-module together with an graded endomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $d:A\to A$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 We think of 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}$
\end_inset

 as being the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We define the 
\series bold
homology 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula $H(A):=\text{Ker}(d)/\text{Im}(d)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $H(A)=\bigoplus_{i\in\mathbb{Z}}H_{i}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 An element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(d)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
cycle 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Im}(d)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
boundary 
\series default
of
\series bold
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.

\series bold
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 be chain complexes over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with differentials 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 A chain map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A\to A'$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as a homogeneous homomorphism of graded 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-modules such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi d=d'\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from the definition that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 takes 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(d)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(d')$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Im}(d)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Im}(d')$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 gies rise to an 
\series bold
induced map on homology
\series default
, which we also call 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:H(A)\to H(A')$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}(A)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{i}:H_{i}(A)\to H_{i}(A')$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Homotopy Equivalence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 be chain maps of chain complexes 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 with differentials 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
homotopic 
\series default
to 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 if there is a graded homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $h:A\to A'$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi-\psi=d'h+hd$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 be chain maps of chain complexes 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

 with differentials 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

 respectively such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is homotopic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 induce the same map on homology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It suffices to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi-\psi$
\end_inset

 induces the 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 map on homology.
 Thus we may simplify the notation by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi-\psi$
\end_inset

, and assume from the outset that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 be a homotopy, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=d'h+dh$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\text{Ker}(d)$
\end_inset

 be a cycle of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 From the formula for the homotopy 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi(a) & =d'(h(a))+h(d(a))\\
 & =d'(h(a))+h(0)\\
 & =d'(h(a)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(a)$
\end_inset

 is a boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 induces the 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 map on homology.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Exact Sequences of Chain Complexes over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A''$
\end_inset

 be chain complexes over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with differentials 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $d''$
\end_inset

 respectively, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:A'\to A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:A\to A''$
\end_inset

 be chain maps.
 Then we say that
\end_layout

